  "text": "WebIDL to C++ DOM Binding Discovery Report\n\nThis report documents the WebIDL interface definitions for the Fetch API and their corresponding C++ binding implementations in the Firefox codebase.\n\n## Request Interface\n- **WebIDL File**: dom/webidl/Request.webidl\n  Defines the Request interface as specified in https://fetch.spec.whatwg.org/#request-class\n- **C++ Header**: dom/fetch/Request.h\n  Contains the Request class declaration that inherits from FetchBody<Request> and nsWrapperCache\n  Includes RequestBinding.h for WebIDL bindings and InternalRequest.h for internal implementation\n- **C++ Implementation**: dom/fetch/Request.cpp\n  Implements the Request interface methods and lifecycle\n\n## Response Interface\n- **WebIDL File**: dom/webidl/Response.webidl\n  Defines the Response interface as specified in https://fetch.spec.whatwg.org/#response-class\n  Includes static factory methods (error, redirect, json) and response properties\n- **C++ Header**: dom/fetch/Response.h\n  Contains the Response class declaration that inherits from FetchBody<Response> and nsWrapperCache\n  Includes ResponseBinding.h for WebIDL bindings and InternalResponse.h for internal implementation\n- **C++ Implementation**: dom/fetch/Response.cpp\n  Implements the Response interface methods and lifecycle\n\n## Headers Interface\n- **WebIDL File**: dom/webidl/Headers.webidl\n  Defines the Headers interface as specified in http://fetch.spec.whatwg.org/#headers-class\n  Includes constructor, manipulation methods (append, delete, get, set, has) and iteration support\n- **C++ Header**: dom/fetch/Headers.h\n  Contains the Headers class that acts as a wrapper around InternalHeaders\n  Includes HeadersBinding.h for WebIDL bindings\n  Note: The Headers class is documented to be used only for content-facing Headers objects\n- **C++ Implementation**: dom/fetch/Headers.cpp\n  Implements the Headers interface methods and wraps InternalHeaders functionality\n\n## FetchEvent Interface\n- **WebIDL File**: dom/webidl/FetchEvent.webidl\n  Defines the FetchEvent interface as specified in the Service Worker specification\n  (http://slightlyoff.github.io/ServiceWorker/spec/service_worker/index.html)\n  Extends ExtendableEvent and provides access to the intercepted request and response handling\n- **C++ Header**: dom/serviceworkers/ServiceWorkerEvents.h\n  Contains the FetchEvent class that extends ExtendableEvent\n  Includes FetchEventBinding.h for WebIDL bindings\n  Manages fetch interception, response handling, and the promise-based respondWith mechanism\n- **C++ Implementation**: dom/serviceworkers/ServiceWorkerEvents.cpp\n  Implements the FetchEvent interface methods and lifecycle\n  Handles service worker fetch interception and event dispatching\n\n## Architecture Notes\n\n1. **WebIDL Binding Files**: While not listed as separate files, the binding headers (RequestBinding.h, ResponseBinding.h, HeadersBinding.h, FetchEventBinding.h) are auto-generated from the WebIDL files and provide the glue code between JavaScript and C++.\n\n2. **Internal Classes**: Many Fetch API implementations use internal classes:\n   - InternalRequest (used by Request)\n   - InternalResponse (used by Response)\n   - InternalHeaders (used by Headers)\n   These separate the public API from internal implementation details.\n\n3. **File Organization**: \n   - Request, Response, and Headers implementations are located in dom/fetch/ as they are core Fetch API types\n   - FetchEvent is located in dom/serviceworkers/ as it is part of the Service Worker specification\n\n4. **Binding Pattern**: All classes follow the pattern of:\n   - Including their auto-generated *Binding.h header\n   - Implementing a WrapObject method that uses the binding's Wrap function\n   - Using nsWrapperCache to manage JavaScript object associations"
